    "summary": "The origins of papermaking in China date to the early Han dynasty, with the oldest known paper fragments (made from hemp and textile fibers) found in tombs dating to around 100–200 BC. The traditional attribution credits the court official Cai Lun (c. 105 AD) with improving and standardizing the process, but archaeological finds predate this by two or more centuries, suggesting Cai Lun refined rather than invented papermaking.\n\nEarly Han paper was made by macerating hemp, rags, and fishing nets into a pulp suspended in water, then draining it through a screen mold to form sheets. Initially used for wrapping and padding rather than writing (bamboo and silk remained the primary writing materials), paper gradually replaced these costlier media as production improved. The eventual spread of Chinese papermaking technology westward via the Silk Road — reaching the Islamic world after the Battle of Talas (751 AD) and eventually medieval Europe — was one of the most consequential technology transfers in history, enabling mass literacy and the spread of printed texts.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_paper",
